    "plainEnglish": "Rheumatic aortic insufficiency means the aortic valve in your heart (which normally prevents blood from flowing backward) has been damaged by rheumatic fever and no longer closes properly. As a result, blood leaks backward into the heart chamber with each heartbeat, forcing your heart to work harder and potentially leading to shortness of breath, fatigue, or swelling in your legs. This is a long-term consequence of untreated or severe rheumatic fever, usually occurring years after the initial infection.",
    "whoUses": "Cardiologists and cardiac surgeons use this code when diagnosing and managing patients with valvular heart disease caused by rheumatic fever. It commonly appears on EOB statements for patients undergoing echocardiograms, cardiac imaging, office visits for heart disease management, and potentially valve replacement surgery consultations.",
