    "code": "I09.2",
    "rawCode": "I092",
    "shortDesc": "Chronic rheumatic pericarditis",
    "longDesc": "Chronic rheumatic pericarditis",
    "plainEnglish": "Chronic rheumatic pericarditis is long-term inflammation of the membrane surrounding your heart (the pericardium) caused by rheumatic fever, usually from a past strep throat infection that wasn't treated properly. This condition causes the pericardium to become thickened and scarred, which can restrict how well your heart fills with blood and lead to symptoms like shortness of breath, chest pain, or fatigue that persist over time. It's a serious complication of untreated or inadequately treated acute rheumatic fever.",
    "whoUses": "Cardiologists and internal medicine physicians use this code when treating patients with long-standing rheumatic heart disease affecting the pericardium. This diagnosis commonly appears on EOBs for patients undergoing cardiac imaging, echocardiography, or specialist consultations to monitor or treat this chronic heart condition.",
