    "shortDesc": "Hypertensive urgency",
    "longDesc": "Hypertensive urgency",
    "plainEnglish": "Hypertensive urgency is a situation where your blood pressure becomes dangerously elevated (usually 180/120 mmHg or higher) and requires immediate medical attention, but without evidence of acute organ damage like a heart attack or stroke. You may experience severe headache, chest discomfort, shortness of breath, or nosebleeds, and your doctor will work quickly to lower your blood pressure safely to prevent it from progressing to a more dangerous condition.",
    "whoUses": "Emergency medicine physicians, urgent care providers, and cardiologists use this code when treating patients who present with severely elevated blood pressure in the ED or urgent care setting. It commonly appears on EOB statements for emergency room or urgent care visits where blood pressure management is the primary reason for the visit.",
