    "shortDesc": "Unstable angina",
    "longDesc": "Unstable angina",
    "plainEnglish": "Unstable angina is chest pain or discomfort caused by reduced blood flow to your heart that occurs unpredictably and may be getting worse. Unlike stable angina (which happens regularly during exertion), unstable angina can strike at rest, with less exertion than usual, or with increasing severity and frequency—and it's a warning sign that a heart attack may be imminent if not treated. You might feel chest pressure, heaviness, or pain that radiates to your arm, neck, or jaw, and it typically doesn't fully go away with rest or your usual heart medications.",
