    "plainEnglish": "This code describes types of chest pain caused by angina that don't fit into the more common categories. Angina happens when your heart isn't getting enough blood flow, usually because of narrowed arteries, and it typically feels like pressure, tightness, or squeezing in your chest. This particular code is used when your chest pain has features of angina but may be caused by unusual circumstances, occur in unexpected patterns, or have characteristics that don't match the standard definitions of stable or unstable angina.",
    "whoUses": "Cardiologists, internists, and emergency medicine doctors use this code when diagnosing and treating patients with atypical or variant forms of angina pectoris. It commonly appears on patient EOB statements, particularly for patients undergoing cardiac evaluation, stress testing, or having chest pain workups in hospital or office settings.",
