    "longDesc": "Myocardial infarction type 2",
    "plainEnglish": "A Type 2 heart attack occurs when your heart muscle doesn't get enough oxygen due to a mismatch between your heart's oxygen supply and demand, rather than from a blocked artery like a typical heart attack. This can happen during severe stress (physical or emotional), severe anemia, very low blood pressure, or other conditions that strain the heart, and may cause chest pain, shortness of breath, or other heart attack symptoms even though the coronary arteries aren't blocked.",
    "whoUses": "Cardiologists, emergency medicine physicians, and hospitalists use this code when diagnosing patients with heart attacks caused by supply-demand imbalances rather than plaque rupture. It commonly appears on EOB statements for patients admitted with acute coronary syndrome symptoms but whose angiography shows no significant arterial blockages.",
