    "longDesc": "Acute coronary thrombosis not resulting in myocardial infarction",
    "plainEnglish": "This code describes a blood clot that forms in one of the arteries supplying your heart, but fortunately the clot didn't completely cut off blood flow enough to cause permanent heart muscle damage (which would be a heart attack). You may have experienced chest pain or other warning signs, but your heart muscle was spared from the permanent injury that defines a full heart attack. This is a serious event that requires immediate treatment to prevent the clot from getting worse.",
    "whoUses": "Cardiologists and emergency medicine physicians use this code when treating patients who arrive with acute coronary syndrome symptoms and imaging shows a clot in a coronary artery without evidence of myocardial infarction. This code appears on EOB statements for patients who had coronary events managed in emergency or acute care settings, typically following urgent catheterization or imaging procedures.",
