    "plainEnglish": "This code describes a buildup of plaque in your heart arteries that has hardened into calcium deposits, restricting blood flow to your heart muscle. Coronary atherosclerosis is the gradual narrowing of arteries that supply blood to your heart, and when calcium accumulates in these plaques, it makes the blockages harder and more rigid. You may experience chest pain, shortness of breath during activity, or have this condition detected during heart imaging tests, even if you haven't noticed symptoms yet.",
    "whoUses": "Cardiologists, interventional cardiologists, and primary care physicians use this code when diagnosing or managing patients with calcified coronary artery disease, typically identified through cardiac catheterization, CT angiography, or stress testing. This code commonly appears on EOB statements for patients undergoing cardiac workup, angiography procedures, or management of known coronary artery disease.",
