    "longDesc": "Septic pulmonary embolism with acute cor pulmonale",
    "plainEnglish": "A septic pulmonary embolism occurs when an infected blood clot travels through your veins to your lungs, where it blocks blood flow and causes a serious infection. This can happen after surgery, from an infected heart valve, or from bacteria entering the bloodstream, and when severe enough, it can damage the right side of your heart (acute cor pulmonale), making it harder for your heart to pump blood effectively. Symptoms typically include sudden chest pain, difficulty breathing, cough, fever, and a rapid or irregular heartbeat.",
