    "rawCode": "I270",
    "shortDesc": "Primary pulmonary hypertension",
    "longDesc": "Primary pulmonary hypertension",
    "plainEnglish": "Primary pulmonary hypertension is a condition where the blood pressure in the arteries of your lungs becomes abnormally high, even though there's no underlying heart or lung disease causing it. This happens because the small blood vessels in your lungs become stiff and narrow, forcing your heart to work much harder to pump blood through them. Over time, this can cause shortness of breath, chest pain, fatigue, and in severe cases, heart failure.",
