    "shortDesc": "Chronic pulmonary embolism",
    "longDesc": "Chronic pulmonary embolism",
    "plainEnglish": "Chronic pulmonary embolism means you have one or more blood clots that have lodged in the blood vessels of your lungs and have been there for a long time (weeks to months or longer), rather than occurring suddenly. Unlike an acute blood clot that causes sudden chest pain and shortness of breath, a chronic clot may develop gradually, causing persistent symptoms like ongoing shortness of breath with exertion, fatigue, or chest discomfort as your lungs struggle to get enough oxygen-rich blood throughout your body.",
    "whoUses": "Pulmonologists, cardiologists, and vascular medicine specialists use this code when managing patients with long-standing pulmonary emboli, particularly those diagnosed on imaging weeks after the initial clot formation or those with recurrent clots. This code commonly appears on EOB statements for patients requiring ongoing anticoagulation therapy, imaging follow-ups, or evaluation for chronic thromboembolic pulmonary hypertension.",
