    "longDesc": "Fontan-associated liver disease [FALD]",
    "plainEnglish": "Fontan-associated liver disease (FALD) is a condition that develops in patients who have had a Fontan procedure, a surgical repair for certain congenital heart defects where the heart's right side is underdeveloped. After this surgery, blood doesn't flow normally through the liver, which can cause scarring and damage to the liver over time. Patients may experience fatigue, fluid buildup, or elevated liver enzymes, though some may have no symptoms initially.",
    "whoUses": "This code is used by cardiologists, hepatologists, and cardiac surgeons who manage patients with complex congenital heart disease and track long-term complications. It commonly appears on EOB statements for patients who had Fontan procedures in childhood and are now presenting with liver complications in adolescence or adulthood.",
