    "plainEnglish": "This code describes a situation where a patient has had or currently relies on a Fontan procedure, a complex heart surgery that reroutes blood flow to bypass a missing or non-functional heart chamber. People with this condition typically have a heart defect present from birth where one of the lower pumping chambers (ventricle) either doesn't develop properly or doesn't work well, so surgeons create an alternative pathway for blood to reach the lungs and the rest of the body. The code is used when doctors are documenting this surgical heart circulation pattern without specifying additional details about the patient's current status or complications.",
    "whoUses": "This code is primarily used by pediatric cardiologists, cardiac surgeons, and general cardiologists who manage patients with complex congenital heart disease. It typically appears in medical records and insurance documents for children and young adults with Fontan procedures, and may be seen on EOB statements when billing for cardiology follow-up visits, imaging studies, or hospitalizations related to monitoring this surgical condition.",
