    "longDesc": "Chronic adhesive pericarditis",
    "plainEnglish": "Chronic adhesive pericarditis means that the thin sac surrounding your heart (the pericardium) has developed scar tissue that causes the inner and outer layers to stick together over time. This sticking prevents the heart from moving and expanding normally with each beat, which can limit how efficiently your heart pumps blood and may cause symptoms like shortness of breath, fatigue, or chest discomfort. It usually develops after inflammation, infection, surgery, or injury to the pericardium has healed, leaving permanent adhesions.",
    "whoUses": "Cardiologists diagnose and manage this condition, often with imaging (echocardiogram or CT scan) and may refer patients to cardiac surgeons if surgical removal of adhesions is needed. It appears on EOB statements when patients receive diagnostic workup or treatment for persistent pericardial restriction.",
