    "longDesc": "Chronic constrictive pericarditis",
    "plainEnglish": "Chronic constrictive pericarditis is a long-term condition where the pericardium—the protective sac around your heart—becomes thick, scarred, and tight, restricting your heart's ability to fill and pump blood normally. This can develop slowly over months or years due to previous inflammation, infection, surgery, or radiation, causing symptoms like shortness of breath, fatigue, swelling in the legs and abdomen, and reduced exercise tolerance. The heart essentially gets \"squeezed\" by the tight pericardial lining, which is why it's called constrictive.",
    "whoUses": "Cardiologists diagnose and manage this condition using echocardiograms, cardiac catheterization, and cardiac imaging; it may also be seen by cardiac surgeons if pericardiectomy (surgical removal of the pericardium) is considered. This code commonly appears on EOB statements for patients undergoing cardiac evaluation, imaging, or surgical intervention for this condition.",
