    "plainEnglish": "Chronic diastolic heart failure means your heart muscle has become stiff and cannot relax properly between heartbeats, making it difficult for the chambers to fill with blood normally. This is different from systolic heart failure (where the heart doesn't pump forcefully enough) — in your case, the pumping action is relatively normal, but the relaxation phase is impaired. Over time, this causes blood to back up into your lungs and body tissues, leading to symptoms like shortness of breath, swelling in your legs and ankles, and fatigue.",
    "whoUses": "Cardiologists, internists, and primary care physicians use this code when diagnosing and managing patients with diastolic dysfunction and heart failure. You will commonly see this code on EOB statements and medical bills related to heart failure office visits, imaging studies, and medications used to treat the condition.",
    "billable": true,
    "isNew": false,
