    "plainEnglish": "Heart failure means your heart is not pumping blood effectively throughout your body, so organs and tissues don't get enough oxygen-rich blood. This can cause shortness of breath, fatigue, swelling in your legs or belly, and difficulty with physical activity. The \"unspecified\" part means the doctor has diagnosed heart failure but hasn't yet determined whether it's due to a weak pumping action (systolic), stiff heart muscles (diastolic), or another specific cause.",
    "whoUses": "Cardiologists, internal medicine doctors, and emergency physicians commonly use this code when a patient presents with heart failure symptoms but the specific type hasn't been determined or documented yet. It appears frequently on patient EOB statements for hospital admissions, cardiology visits, and emergency department encounters, though it's often a temporary coding assignment that gets updated to a more specific heart failure code once testing is complete.",
    "billable": true,
