    "longDesc": "Cardiac septal defect, acquired",
    "plainEnglish": "An acquired cardiac septal defect means a hole has developed in the wall (septum) that separates the chambers of your heart—this is different from a birth defect, as it developed sometime after you were born, often due to a heart attack, infection, or other heart disease. This hole allows blood to flow abnormally between the heart chambers, which can cause your heart to work less efficiently and may lead to symptoms like shortness of breath, fatigue, or irregular heartbeats.",
    "whoUses": "Cardiologists and cardiac surgeons use this code when diagnosing and treating patients with septal defects that develop after birth, typically identified during echocardiograms or cardiac imaging. This code commonly appears on EOB statements for patients undergoing cardiac evaluation, imaging studies, or surgical intervention for heart defects.",
