    "longDesc": "Rupture of chordae tendineae, not elsewhere classified",
    "plainEnglish": "The chordae tendineae are small, thin cords inside your heart that attach your heart valve to the heart muscle and help it open and close properly. When these cords rupture or snap, the valve can no longer function correctly, which means blood may leak backward through the valve instead of flowing in one direction. This can cause your heart to work harder and may lead to symptoms like shortness of breath, fatigue, or chest discomfort.",
    "whoUses": "Cardiologists and cardiac surgeons use this code when diagnosing and treating patients with chordae tendineae rupture, often identified through echocardiography. It commonly appears on EOB statements for patients undergoing cardiac imaging, consultation, or valve repair/replacement surgery.",
