    "longDesc": "Rupture of papillary muscle, not elsewhere classified",
    "plainEnglish": "A papillary muscle is a small muscle inside your heart that helps control your mitral valve—one of the four valves that keeps blood flowing in the right direction. When this muscle ruptures or tears, it can no longer support the valve properly, which may cause blood to leak backward into your heart and lungs. This is a serious condition that typically develops after a heart attack and can cause chest pain, shortness of breath, and heart failure symptoms.",
    "whoUses": "Cardiologists and cardiac surgeons use this code when diagnosing and treating patients with papillary muscle rupture, usually after acute myocardial infarction. This is a serious, often acute condition that typically appears on EOB statements for hospitalized patients requiring emergency cardiac care or surgery rather than routine outpatient visits.",
