    "shortDesc": "Takotsubo syndrome",
    "longDesc": "Takotsubo syndrome",
    "plainEnglish": "Takotsubo syndrome is a temporary heart condition where the main pumping chamber of your heart (the left ventricle) suddenly weakens, usually triggered by severe emotional or physical stress. The affected part of your heart takes on a distinctive shape resembling a Japanese octopus trap (takotsubo), which is how the condition got its name. Patients typically experience chest pain, shortness of breath, and heart attack-like symptoms, but unlike a traditional heart attack, the coronary arteries are usually not blocked—the weakness is caused by a surge of stress hormones.",
    "whoUses": "Cardiologists and emergency medicine physicians use this code when evaluating patients presenting with acute heart failure symptoms, chest pain, or suspected heart attack, especially those with a clear emotional or physical stressor preceding their symptoms. This code appears on EOBs for patients who have undergone cardiac testing (EKG, echocardiogram, or cardiac catheterization) and received a diagnosis of stress cardiomyopathy.",
