    "longDesc": "Nontraumatic subarachnoid hemorrhage from right carotid siphon and bifurcation",
    "plainEnglish": "A nontraumatic subarachnoid hemorrhage from the right carotid siphon and bifurcation means you've had unexpected bleeding into the space surrounding your brain (the subarachnoid space) caused by a rupture in a major blood vessel on the right side of your neck called the carotid artery, specifically where it curves (the siphon) or splits (the bifurcation). This is a serious medical emergency that typically causes a sudden, severe headache, and it occurs without any head trauma or injury—meaning it happened spontaneously, often due to an aneurysm (a weakened blood vessel bulge) that burst.",
    "whoUses": "Neurologists, neurosurgeons, emergency medicine physicians, and intensive care specialists use this code when diagnosing and treating patients who present with a ruptured aneurysm or other bleeding from the carotid artery. This code typically appears on EOB statements following emergency hospitalization and would be accompanied by significant charges for imaging, surgery, and critical care.",
