    "plainEnglish": "This code describes bleeding that occurs in the space around your brain (called the subarachnoid space) caused by a rupture of an artery on the left side of your neck called the vertebral artery—not from an injury or trauma. This type of bleeding is a medical emergency because blood in this area puts pressure on the brain and can cause sudden severe headache, neck stiffness, confusion, or stroke-like symptoms. The vertebral artery rupture happens spontaneously, often due to a weak spot in the artery wall (aneurysm) that bursts on its own.",
    "whoUses": "Neurologists, neurosurgeons, emergency medicine physicians, and intensivists use this code when treating patients with spontaneous bleeding in the brain. This diagnosis typically appears on EOB statements after emergency department visits, hospital stays, or neurosurgical interventions for subarachnoid hemorrhage.",
