    "plainEnglish": "A subarachnoid hemorrhage (SAH) is serious bleeding in the space surrounding your brain, between the brain tissue and the protective membrane that covers it. This bleeding happens spontaneously—not from a head injury—and can be caused by a ruptured blood vessel or aneurysm, high blood pressure, or a bleeding disorder. Patients typically experience a sudden, severe \"thunderclap\" headache (often described as the worst headache of their life), along with stiff neck, sensitivity to light, nausea, vomiting, and sometimes loss of consciousness or seizures.",
