    "rawCode": "I6201",
    "shortDesc": "Nontraumatic acute subdural hemorrhage",
    "longDesc": "Nontraumatic acute subdural hemorrhage",
    "plainEnglish": "A nontraumatic acute subdural hemorrhage is bleeding that occurs between the outermost membrane covering your brain and the brain tissue itself, without being caused by a head injury. This bleeding can happen spontaneously due to conditions like high blood pressure, blood clotting disorders, or weakened blood vessels, and it represents a medical emergency because the accumulated blood can put dangerous pressure on your brain. Symptoms typically develop suddenly and may include severe headache, confusion, weakness on one side of the body, or loss of consciousness.",
    "whoUses": "Neurologists, neurosurgeons, emergency medicine physicians, and intensivists use this code when diagnosing and treating patients presenting with acute bleeding in the subdural space. It commonly appears on EOB statements for emergency department visits, hospital admissions, and neurosurgical interventions, as this is a serious condition requiring immediate medical attention.",
