    "shortDesc": "Nontraumatic subacute subdural hemorrhage",
    "longDesc": "Nontraumatic subacute subdural hemorrhage",
    "plainEnglish": "A subacute subdural hemorrhage is bleeding that occurs in the space between your brain and the outermost membrane covering it (called the dura), but without a recent head injury as the cause. This type of bleeding develops slowly over several days to weeks and is more common in elderly patients or those taking blood thinners, where minor falls or even spontaneous bleeding can trigger it. Symptoms may include headaches, confusion, weakness, or difficulty with balance as the blood gradually accumulates and puts pressure on the brain.",
    "whoUses": "Neurologists, neurosurgeons, and emergency medicine physicians diagnose and manage this condition, often using CT or MRI imaging. This code typically appears on EOB statements for patients admitted to the hospital or receiving imaging studies and specialist consultations for evaluation of neurological symptoms.",
