    "plainEnglish": "A chronic subdural hemorrhage is bleeding that occurs in the space between the brain and the membrane covering it, but happens without a head injury. This bleeding develops slowly over weeks or months, meaning the blood accumulates gradually rather than suddenly. Patients may experience headaches, confusion, memory problems, weakness on one side of the body, or balance problems, and symptoms can mimic a stroke or dementia depending on how much blood has accumulated.",
    "whoUses": "Neurologists, neurosurgeons, and emergency medicine physicians commonly use this code when diagnosing and treating patients with chronic subdural bleeds, often discovered on CT or MRI scans. This diagnosis frequently appears on patient EOB statements because it often requires imaging studies, hospital admission, and sometimes surgical drainage of the accumulated blood.",
