    "rawCode": "I6319",
    "shortDesc": "Cerebral infarction due to embolism of precerebral artery",
    "longDesc": "Cerebral infarction due to embolism of other precerebral artery",
    "plainEnglish": "This code describes a stroke caused by a blood clot that traveled through one of the major arteries in your neck or upper chest (the carotid or vertebral arteries) and lodged in a blood vessel in your brain, blocking blood flow. The clot came from somewhere else in your body—often the heart, aorta, or another artery—and traveled to your brain where it caused brain tissue to die from lack of oxygen. You likely experienced sudden symptoms like weakness, numbness, difficulty speaking, or vision problems.",
    "whoUses": "Neurologists, stroke specialists, emergency medicine physicians, and hospitalists use this code when diagnosing and treating acute ischemic stroke patients in emergency departments and stroke centers. This code appears frequently on patient EOB statements when someone has been hospitalized for acute stroke care, as it documents the specific cause and location of the blockage for billing and medical record purposes.",
    "billable": true,
    "isNew": false,
    "isRevised": false,
