    "longDesc": "Cerebral infarction, unspecified",
    "plainEnglish": "A cerebral infarction, unspecified means you've had a stroke caused by a blood clot blocking blood flow to the brain, but the doctor hasn't documented which specific area of the brain was affected or the exact cause. Your brain cells in the affected area don't get enough oxygen and can become damaged or die, which can cause symptoms like weakness, numbness, speech problems, or loss of consciousness depending on which part of the brain was affected.",
    "whoUses": "Neurologists, emergency medicine physicians, and hospitalists commonly use this code when a patient presents with acute stroke symptoms. It typically appears on EOB statements during hospital admissions for acute stroke care, emergency department visits, or follow-up neurology consultations, though it may be refined to a more specific stroke code (I63.0-I63.8) once imaging and clinical details are documented.",
