    "shortDesc": "Occlusion and stenosis of left vertebral artery",
    "longDesc": "Occlusion and stenosis of left vertebral artery",
    "plainEnglish": "This diagnosis means that the vertebral artery on the left side of your neck is partially or completely blocked, reducing blood flow to the back of your brain. The vertebral arteries are major blood vessels that supply oxygen-rich blood to important parts of your brain, and when one becomes narrowed or closed off, it can increase your risk of stroke or cause symptoms like dizziness, balance problems, or vision changes. This blockage can develop from plaque buildup (atherosclerosis), blood clots, or other vascular conditions.",
    "whoUses": "Neurologists, vascular surgeons, interventional radiologists, and cardiologists commonly use this code when diagnosing and treating stroke risk or managing cerebrovascular disease. It typically appears on EOB statements when imaging studies (like ultrasound or angiography) or clinical events lead to this diagnosis, and may be associated with treatment planning or monitoring rather than as a primary acute condition code.",
