    "shortDesc": "Hypertensive encephalopathy",
    "longDesc": "Hypertensive encephalopathy",
    "plainEnglish": "Hypertensive encephalopathy is a serious condition where very high blood pressure damages the brain and causes swelling, leading to symptoms like severe headaches, confusion, vision problems, seizures, or loss of consciousness. This is a medical emergency that occurs when blood pressure becomes dangerously elevated and the brain can no longer regulate blood flow properly, allowing fluid to leak into brain tissue. Without prompt treatment to lower blood pressure, this condition can cause permanent brain damage or be life-threatening.",
    "whoUses": "Neurologists, emergency medicine physicians, and intensive care specialists use this code when treating patients with hypertensive crisis affecting the brain. This code appears on EOBs when patients are hospitalized or treated in emergency departments for this acute, severe condition, as it typically requires hospital-level care rather than outpatient management.",
