    "shortDesc": "Acute cerebrovascular insufficiency",
    "longDesc": "Acute cerebrovascular insufficiency",
    "plainEnglish": "Acute cerebrovascular insufficiency means that blood flow to your brain has suddenly decreased, depriving brain tissue of oxygen. This is a serious medical emergency that can happen due to a blood clot, narrowed blood vessels, or other blockages affecting the arteries supplying your brain. You might experience sudden symptoms like weakness, numbness, difficulty speaking, vision changes, or dizziness—the same warning signs as a stroke.",
    "whoUses": "Neurologists, emergency medicine physicians, and intensivists use this code when patients present with sudden reduced blood flow to the brain that hasn't yet caused permanent damage. It commonly appears on hospital bills and EOB statements for emergency department visits or hospital admissions involving acute neurological symptoms.",
