    "rawCode": "I6783",
    "shortDesc": "Posterior reversible encephalopathy syndrome",
    "longDesc": "Posterior reversible encephalopathy syndrome",
    "plainEnglish": "Posterior reversible encephalopathy syndrome (PRES) is a serious but potentially reversible brain condition where brain swelling occurs in the back portions of the brain, usually triggered by severely high blood pressure, certain medications, or other acute medical conditions. Patients typically experience severe headaches, vision changes, confusion, seizures, or weakness. The good news is that if the underlying cause is treated quickly—such as controlling blood pressure or stopping a triggering medication—the brain swelling can resolve without permanent damage.",
    "whoUses": "Neurologists, emergency medicine physicians, intensivists, and neuroradiologists diagnose and manage PRES, often using MRI imaging for confirmation. This code appears on EOB statements when patients are hospitalized with acute neurological symptoms requiring imaging and monitoring, particularly in the emergency or intensive care setting.",
