    "shortDesc": "Reversible cerebrovascular vasoconstriction syndrome",
    "longDesc": "Reversible cerebrovascular vasoconstriction syndrome",
    "plainEnglish": "Reversible cerebrovascular vasoconstriction syndrome (RCVS) is a temporary condition where the blood vessels in your brain become abnormally narrowed or constricted, reducing blood flow to brain tissue. This usually happens suddenly and can cause severe thunderclap headaches, stroke-like symptoms, or seizures, but the good news is that the blood vessel narrowing typically resolves on its own within weeks to months without permanent damage. The condition is often triggered by medications, pregnancy-related complications, intense emotional or physical stress, or certain illicit drugs.",
    "whoUses": "Neurologists and neuroradiologists primarily diagnose and manage RCVS, often in emergency or stroke center settings after imaging studies like angiography reveal the characteristic narrowing pattern. This code appears on EOBs for patients who have experienced acute neurological symptoms leading to hospitalization, imaging studies, or specialist consultations, though it is relatively uncommon compared to other neurological conditions.",
