    "rawCode": "I680",
    "shortDesc": "Cerebral amyloid angiopathy",
    "longDesc": "Cerebral amyloid angiopathy",
    "plainEnglish": "Cerebral amyloid angiopathy is a condition where abnormal protein deposits (called amyloid) build up in the walls of blood vessels in the brain. This buildup weakens the blood vessel walls, making them more likely to leak or rupture, which can cause bleeding in the brain (stroke) or cognitive problems. Patients with this condition may experience unexplained brain bleeds, memory loss, or confusion, and it's often discovered after a stroke or through brain imaging.",
    "whoUses": "Neurologists, neurosurgeons, and stroke specialists use this code when diagnosing patients with brain bleeds or cognitive decline caused by amyloid deposits in cerebral blood vessels. This code appears moderately often on patient EOBs after hospitalization for stroke or when advanced brain imaging is performed, particularly in older adults.",
    "billable": true,
    "isNew": false,
    "isRevised": false,
    "chapterId": 9,
