    "rawCode": "I69020",
    "shortDesc": "Aphasia following nontraumatic subarachnoid hemorrhage",
    "longDesc": "Aphasia following nontraumatic subarachnoid hemorrhage",
    "plainEnglish": "Aphasia following a nontraumatic subarachnoid hemorrhage means you have difficulty speaking, understanding words, or both as a result of bleeding that occurred in the space surrounding your brain (not caused by an injury). A subarachnoid hemorrhage typically happens when a weakened blood vessel ruptures, and the bleeding damages the brain areas responsible for speech and language. You might struggle to find words, speak in incomplete sentences, or have trouble comprehending what others say to you.",
    "whoUses": "Neurologists, neurosurgeons, and rehabilitation specialists (speech-language pathologists) use this code when treating patients recovering from a bleeding stroke. This code commonly appears on EOB statements for patients receiving inpatient stroke care, rehabilitation therapy, or follow-up neurology visits focused on speech and language recovery.",
