    "code": "I69.090",
    "rawCode": "I69090",
    "shortDesc": "Apraxia following nontraumatic subarachnoid hemorrhage",
    "longDesc": "Apraxia following nontraumatic subarachnoid hemorrhage",
    "plainEnglish": "Apraxia is a problem where your brain has difficulty planning or executing voluntary movements, even though your muscles work fine and you understand what you want to do. In this case, it developed after you had a nontraumatic subarachnoid hemorrhage—bleeding in the space around your brain that wasn't caused by an injury or trauma. This bleeding can damage brain areas that control movement coordination, leaving you struggling to perform purposeful movements like reaching, writing, or getting dressed.",
    "whoUses": "Neurologists, physiatrists (rehabilitation doctors), and neuropsychologists use this code when documenting stroke recovery or brain hemorrhage complications. It commonly appears on EOB statements for patients undergoing rehabilitation therapy following a subarachnoid hemorrhage, as insurance companies track functional deficits to justify ongoing physical and occupational therapy.",
