    "longDesc": "Dysphagia following nontraumatic subarachnoid hemorrhage",
    "plainEnglish": "This code describes difficulty swallowing that developed as a complication after a person had bleeding in the space surrounding the brain (a subarachnoid hemorrhage that wasn't caused by an injury). The bleeding in that area can damage the nerves and brain regions that control swallowing, leaving a person with trouble moving food or liquid down their throat safely.",
    "whoUses": "Neurologists, neurosurgeons, hospitalists, and rehabilitation specialists use this code when treating stroke or hemorrhage patients who develop swallowing problems during recovery. This code commonly appears on EOB statements for patients hospitalized with brain bleeding, as it indicates a secondary complication requiring speech-language pathology evaluation and modified diet management.",
