    "rawCode": "I69092",
    "shortDesc": "Facial weakness following ntrm subarachnoid hemorrhage",
    "longDesc": "Facial weakness following nontraumatic subarachnoid hemorrhage",
    "plainEnglish": "You had bleeding in the space around your brain (a subarachnoid hemorrhage) that wasn't caused by trauma or injury, and as a result, the muscles on one side of your face have become weak or partially paralyzed. This facial weakness happens because the bleeding damaged the nerve that controls facial movement. You may notice drooping on one side of your face, difficulty smiling, or weakness when you try to move that side of your face.",
    "whoUses": "Neurologists, neurosurgeons, and stroke specialists use this code when treating patients recovering from subarachnoid hemorrhage who have developed facial nerve dysfunction. This code commonly appears on hospital discharge summaries and EOBs for inpatient neurorehabilitation or follow-up neurology visits, particularly during the acute and recovery phases after the hemorrhage.",
