    "shortDesc": "Ataxia following nontraumatic subarachnoid hemorrhage",
    "longDesc": "Ataxia following nontraumatic subarachnoid hemorrhage",
    "plainEnglish": "This code describes a loss of coordination and balance that developed after a spontaneous bleeding in the space around the brain (not caused by an injury or trauma). When blood vessels in this area rupture on their own, it can damage the parts of the brain that control movement and coordination, leaving someone with difficulty walking, tremors, or unsteady movements even after the bleeding has stopped. This is a long-term complication that patients may experience during recovery or rehabilitation.",
    "whoUses": "Neurologists, neurosurgeons, and stroke specialists use this code when documenting recovery or follow-up care after a patient has had a spontaneous brain bleed. This code commonly appears on EOB statements for patients in the months or years following a subarachnoid hemorrhage, particularly when they're receiving outpatient rehabilitation or neurology follow-up care.",
