    "rawCode": "I69098",
    "shortDesc": "Oth sequelae following nontraumatic subarachnoid hemorrhage",
    "longDesc": "Other sequelae following nontraumatic subarachnoid hemorrhage",
    "plainEnglish": "This code describes long-term complications that occur after someone has had a nontraumatic subarachnoid hemorrhage—a type of brain bleed that happens spontaneously (not from trauma), typically from a burst blood vessel or aneurysm in the space surrounding the brain. The 'other sequelae' means there are lingering effects or problems that develop as a result of that initial bleed, which could include physical weakness, speech difficulties, cognitive problems, or other neurological issues that persist after the acute emergency has been treated.",
    "whoUses": "Neurologists, neurosurgeons, and primary care physicians use this code during follow-up care and rehabilitation of stroke/brain hemorrhage patients. It commonly appears on EOB statements for patients in recovery phases or ongoing therapy appointments related to their previous brain bleed.",
