    "rawCode": "I69113",
    "shortDesc": "Psychomotor deficit following ntrm intcrbl hemorrhage",
    "longDesc": "Psychomotor deficit following nontraumatic intracerebral hemorrhage",
    "plainEnglish": "This code describes difficulty with coordinated movement and motor control that results from bleeding inside the brain. When blood vessels in the brain rupture and cause bleeding (not from an injury), it can damage the areas that control how your muscles move and coordinate, leading to problems like weakness, clumsiness, or difficulty with fine motor tasks like writing or buttoning clothes. This is a long-term consequence of the brain bleed, documented to track your recovery and ongoing physical limitations.",
    "whoUses": "Neurologists, physiatrists (rehabilitation specialists), and primary care physicians use this code when documenting the lasting motor and coordination problems a patient experiences after surviving a stroke caused by brain bleeding. It commonly appears in rehabilitation settings and on EOB statements when patients are receiving ongoing therapy or follow-up care for stroke recovery.",
