    "code": "I69.120",
    "rawCode": "I69120",
    "shortDesc": "Aphasia following nontraumatic intracerebral hemorrhage",
    "longDesc": "Aphasia following nontraumatic intracerebral hemorrhage",
    "plainEnglish": "Aphasia is a language disorder where someone has difficulty speaking, understanding speech, or both—often caused by damage to the language centers of the brain. In this case, the aphasia developed after a stroke caused by bleeding inside the brain (not from an injury or trauma). Depending on the type and severity, a person with aphasia might struggle to find words, speak in incomplete sentences, understand what others say, or have difficulty with reading and writing.",
    "whoUses": "Neurologists, speech-language pathologists, physiatrists (rehabilitation doctors), and stroke specialists use this code when documenting the language complications following a spontaneous brain bleed. It commonly appears on EOB statements for patients receiving speech therapy or neurological rehabilitation services after a stroke.",
