    "shortDesc": "Dysphasia following nontraumatic intracerebral hemorrhage",
    "longDesc": "Dysphasia following nontraumatic intracerebral hemorrhage",
    "plainEnglish": "You had bleeding inside your brain (not from an injury), and as a result, you're now experiencing difficulty with speaking or understanding speech. This happens because the bleeding damaged the parts of your brain that control language. Depending on how severe the bleeding was and which area was affected, you might have trouble finding words, speaking clearly, or understanding what others say to you.",
    "whoUses": "Neurologists, stroke specialists, speech-language pathologists, and physiatrists (rehabilitation doctors) use this code when treating patients recovering from a brain hemorrhage. It commonly appears on EOB statements for patients who've had a stroke and are receiving speech therapy or inpatient rehabilitation services.",
