    "rawCode": "I69122",
    "shortDesc": "Dysarthria following nontraumatic intracerebral hemorrhage",
    "longDesc": "Dysarthria following nontraumatic intracerebral hemorrhage",
    "plainEnglish": "Dysarthria is difficulty speaking clearly—your words may sound slurred, hoarse, or hard to understand—and in this case it happened because you had bleeding inside your brain that wasn't caused by an injury or trauma. The bleeding damaged areas of your brain that control the muscles used for speech, making it hard to pronounce words properly or control the pace and volume of your voice. This is a long-term effect you may experience as you recover from the stroke.",
    "whoUses": "Neurologists, stroke specialists, physiatrists (rehabilitation doctors), and speech-language pathologists use this code when treating patients recovering from intracerebral hemorrhage with resulting speech difficulties. It commonly appears on EOB statements for patients receiving speech therapy or neurological follow-up care after a bleeding stroke.",
