    "longDesc": "Fluency disorder following nontraumatic intracerebral hemorrhage",
    "plainEnglish": "This code describes a speech problem that developed after someone had bleeding inside their brain (not from an injury). The bleeding damaged areas of the brain that control how smoothly we speak, causing the person to stutter, repeat words, or have trouble with the rhythm and flow of their speech. This is one of several possible effects someone might experience while recovering from a brain hemorrhage.",
    "whoUses": "Neurologists, speech-language pathologists, and rehabilitation specialists use this code when documenting post-stroke or post-hemorrhage speech difficulties in patients undergoing physical or speech therapy. It commonly appears on EOB statements for patients receiving outpatient speech therapy following a brain bleed.",
