    "shortDesc": "Dysphagia following nontraumatic intracerebral hemorrhage",
    "longDesc": "Dysphagia following nontraumatic intracerebral hemorrhage",
    "plainEnglish": "This code describes difficulty swallowing that developed after a stroke caused by bleeding in the brain (not from an injury or trauma). When bleeding occurs in the brain tissue itself, it can damage the areas that control swallowing, making it hard for you to eat or drink safely. This puts you at risk for food or liquid going into your lungs instead of your stomach, which can cause serious complications like pneumonia.",
    "whoUses": "Neurologists, stroke specialists, speech-language pathologists, and hospitalists commonly use this code when managing stroke patients in acute care or rehabilitation settings. It frequently appears on EOB statements for patients hospitalized or receiving rehabilitation services following an intracerebral hemorrhage event.",
