    "plainEnglish": "Aphasia following other nontraumatic intracranial hemorrhage means you've lost some ability to communicate—speaking, understanding, reading, or writing—as a result of bleeding inside your brain that wasn't caused by an injury or trauma. This happens because the hemorrhage (bleeding) damaged the language centers of your brain, and the recovery of these communication abilities depends on the extent and location of the brain damage. You might struggle to find words, have difficulty understanding what others say, or experience a combination of these communication problems.",
