    "longDesc": "Dysarthria following other nontraumatic intracranial hemorrhage",
    "plainEnglish": "This code describes difficulty with speech and articulation (how clearly you pronounce words) that developed after a stroke caused by bleeding in the brain, rather than from a head injury. The bleeding damaged areas of the brain responsible for controlling the muscles used in speech, making it harder to form words clearly even though you understand what you want to say. You might sound slurred, slow, or have trouble controlling your speech muscles.",
    "whoUses": "Neurologists, speech-language pathologists, and primary care doctors use this code during and after hospitalization or rehabilitation for non-traumatic brain bleeds like intracerebral hemorrhage or subarachnoid hemorrhage. This code commonly appears on EOB statements as a secondary diagnosis linked to stroke recovery and rehabilitation services.",
    "billable": true,
    "isNew": false,
    "isRevised": false,
    "chapterId": 9,
