    "rawCode": "I69291",
    "shortDesc": "Dysphagia following oth nontraumatic intracranial hemorrhage",
    "longDesc": "Dysphagia following other nontraumatic intracranial hemorrhage",
    "plainEnglish": "Dysphagia following other nontraumatic intracranial hemorrhage means you're having difficulty swallowing as a result of bleeding in the brain that wasn't caused by an injury or trauma. This swallowing problem occurs because the bleeding damaged areas of the brain that control the muscles and nerves involved in swallowing. You might experience choking, coughing when eating or drinking, or food/liquid going into your airway.",
    "whoUses": "Neurologists, stroke specialists, physiatrists (rehabilitation doctors), and speech-language pathologists use this code when treating patients recovering from spontaneous brain bleeds such as those from aneurysms or arteriovenous malformations. It commonly appears on EOB statements for patients receiving inpatient rehabilitation or ongoing swallowing therapy after a hemorrhagic stroke.",
