    "rawCode": "I69292",
    "shortDesc": "Facial weakness following oth nontraumatic intcrn hemorrhage",
    "longDesc": "Facial weakness following other nontraumatic intracranial hemorrhage",
    "plainEnglish": "This code describes facial weakness that developed after a bleeding event inside the brain (not caused by injury). When bleeding occurs in the brain from causes like high blood pressure or ruptured blood vessels, it can damage the nerves that control the muscles in your face, resulting in drooping, difficulty moving one side of your face, or weakness when smiling or closing your eye. This weakness is a lingering effect of the brain bleed and is coded separately to track your recovery from this complication.",
    "whoUses": "Neurologists, stroke specialists (interventional neuroradiologists), and physiatrists (rehabilitation doctors) use this code when treating patients recovering from intracranial hemorrhage who have developed facial weakness as a residual effect. It commonly appears on EOB statements for patients in acute care or rehabilitation settings following a stroke or brain hemorrhage event.",
