    "longDesc": "Ataxia following other nontraumatic intracranial hemorrhage",
    "plainEnglish": "Ataxia is a loss of coordination and balance that develops after someone has had bleeding inside the brain (not caused by an injury). This condition occurs as a complication of the brain bleed itself, affecting the parts of the brain that control movement and balance. A patient with this diagnosis might experience difficulty walking, clumsiness, tremors, or trouble with fine motor tasks like writing or eating.",
    "whoUses": "Neurologists, neurological rehabilitation specialists, and physiatrists (physical medicine and rehabilitation doctors) commonly use this code when treating patients recovering from stroke or intracerebral hemorrhage. This code typically appears on EOB statements for patients undergoing rehabilitation therapy or neurology follow-up care after a bleeding event in the brain.",
