    "rawCode": "I6930",
    "shortDesc": "Unspecified sequelae of cerebral infarction",
    "longDesc": "Unspecified sequelae of cerebral infarction",
    "plainEnglish": "This code indicates that you had a stroke (cerebral infarction) in the past, and you're now experiencing long-term effects from that stroke, but the specific type of problem hasn't been clearly identified or documented yet. Stroke can cause lasting difficulties like weakness, speech problems, memory issues, or difficulty walking, depending on which part of the brain was affected. This code is used when a patient is being treated for these lingering problems but the exact nature of the remaining disability needs further evaluation or isn't specified in the medical record.",
    "whoUses": "Neurologists, primary care physicians, physical medicine and rehabilitation specialists, and hospitalists commonly use this code when following up with stroke patients in outpatient or inpatient settings. It frequently appears on EOB statements for patients undergoing rehabilitation or long-term stroke recovery care, and is especially common when documenting ongoing complications from a prior stroke event.",
