    "rawCode": "I69320",
    "shortDesc": "Aphasia following cerebral infarction",
    "longDesc": "Aphasia following cerebral infarction",
    "plainEnglish": "Aphasia following cerebral infarction means you have difficulty speaking, understanding, reading, or writing because of a stroke (brain attack) that damaged the language centers in your brain. When blood flow to the brain is blocked by a clot or plaque, brain cells die and can no longer control language abilities—even though you still have your thoughts and intelligence intact. Depending on which part of the brain was affected, you might struggle to find words, understand what others say, or form complete sentences.",
    "whoUses": "Neurologists, stroke specialists, and rehabilitation medicine physicians use this code when documenting stroke recovery and language deficits. Speech-language pathologists also reference it for therapy planning. This code commonly appears on patient EOBs for stroke-related rehabilitation services, speech therapy, and follow-up neurology visits.",
