    "plainEnglish": "Dysphasia following cerebral infarction means you have difficulty speaking or expressing yourself clearly because you've had a stroke caused by a blood clot blocking blood flow to your brain. This language problem occurs after the stroke damages the areas of your brain that control speech. You might struggle to find words, have trouble forming sentences, or experience difficulty understanding what others say to you.",
    "whoUses": "Neurologists, stroke specialists, speech-language pathologists, and rehabilitation medicine doctors use this code when treating stroke patients who develop speech or language difficulties during recovery. It commonly appears on EOB statements for patients undergoing inpatient or outpatient speech therapy and stroke rehabilitation services.",
