    "plainEnglish": "Dysarthria following cerebral infarction means you have difficulty speaking or slurred speech as a result of a stroke (blood clot or bleeding in the brain). The stroke damaged the parts of your brain that control the muscles used for speech, making it hard to form words clearly or speak smoothly, even though you still understand language and know what you want to say. This is a common side effect of stroke recovery.",
    "whoUses": "Neurologists, physiatrists (rehabilitation doctors), speech-language pathologists, and primary care physicians use this code when treating stroke patients with speech difficulties. It commonly appears on EOB statements for patients recovering from stroke who receive speech therapy or ongoing neurological care.",
