    "code": "I69.390",
    "rawCode": "I69390",
    "shortDesc": "Apraxia following cerebral infarction",
    "longDesc": "Apraxia following cerebral infarction",
    "plainEnglish": "Apraxia is a neurological condition where your brain has difficulty planning and coordinating movements, even though your muscles are working fine. This specific code indicates that apraxia developed as a result of a stroke (cerebral infarction) that damaged the parts of your brain responsible for movement planning. You might experience difficulty with tasks like dressing, eating, or writing despite having normal muscle strength and sensation.",
    "whoUses": "Neurologists, stroke specialists, and rehabilitation medicine physicians use this code when documenting post-stroke recovery. It commonly appears on EOB statements for patients undergoing physical or occupational therapy following a stroke, as it helps justify ongoing rehabilitation services.",
