    "shortDesc": "Facial weakness following cerebral infarction",
    "longDesc": "Facial weakness following cerebral infarction",
    "plainEnglish": "Facial weakness following cerebral infarction means that after a stroke (caused by a blood clot or blocked artery in the brain), you have developed weakness or drooping in the muscles on one side of your face. This happens because the stroke damaged the part of your brain that controls facial movement, so signals from your brain to your face muscles aren't working properly. You might notice that one side of your face droops, your smile looks uneven, or you have trouble closing your eye on the affected side.",
    "whoUses": "Neurologists, stroke specialists, and physiatrists (rehabilitation doctors) commonly use this code when treating stroke patients who develop facial weakness during recovery. This code appears on EOBs for patients receiving inpatient or outpatient stroke rehabilitation, neurology follow-up visits, and physical or occupational therapy services related to facial muscle recovery.",
