    "plainEnglish": "Ataxia following cerebral infarction means you're experiencing problems with balance, coordination, and muscle control after having a stroke caused by a blood clot in the brain. A stroke can damage the parts of your brain that control movement and balance, leaving you feeling unsteady, clumsy, or having difficulty walking even after the immediate stroke has been treated. This condition develops as a complication of the stroke itself, not as a separate problem.",
    "whoUses": "Neurologists, rehabilitation medicine specialists, and physiatrists commonly use this code when treating stroke recovery patients who develop coordination problems during inpatient or outpatient rehabilitation. This code typically appears on EOB statements for patients undergoing physical therapy or neurology follow-up visits after a documented stroke.",
