    "shortDesc": "Dysarthria following other cerebrovascular disease",
    "longDesc": "Dysarthria following other cerebrovascular disease",
    "plainEnglish": "Dysarthria is difficulty speaking clearly—your words may sound slurred, mumbled, or hard to understand—that developed after you had a stroke or other brain blood vessel problem (not the most common types of stroke). This happens because the stroke damaged the parts of your brain that control the muscles used for speech, even though you can still think and understand language normally.",
    "whoUses": "Neurologists, stroke specialists, and speech-language pathologists use this code when treating patients recovering from less common cerebrovascular events like vasculitis or venous thrombosis. It commonly appears on EOBs when documenting post-stroke speech therapy or neurological follow-up visits.",
    "billable": true,
    "isNew": false,
    "isRevised": false,
    "chapterId": 9,
    "chapterTitle": "Diseases of the circulatory system",
