    "shortDesc": "Ataxia following other cerebrovascular disease",
    "longDesc": "Ataxia following other cerebrovascular disease",
    "plainEnglish": "Ataxia following other cerebrovascular disease means you have lost coordination and balance as a result of a stroke or other blood vessel problem in your brain that isn't covered by the more common stroke categories. Ataxia causes difficulty with movement, walking, and fine motor control like writing or picking up small objects. This happens when the part of your brain that controls coordination has been damaged by interrupted blood flow.",
    "whoUses": "Neurologists, physiatrists (rehabilitation specialists), and stroke specialists use this code when documenting long-term effects of stroke recovery. It commonly appears on EOB statements as a secondary diagnosis code for patients in ongoing rehabilitation or neurology follow-up care after a stroke.",
