    "code": "I69.921",
    "rawCode": "I69921",
    "shortDesc": "Dysphasia following unspecified cerebrovascular disease",
    "longDesc": "Dysphasia following unspecified cerebrovascular disease",
    "plainEnglish": "Dysphasia is a difficulty with speaking or expressing yourself clearly, and in this case it happened as a complication after you had a stroke or other blood vessel problem in the brain. You may struggle to find the right words, speak slowly, or have trouble forming sentences, even though you understand what others are saying. This condition is a lingering effect of the original brain injury and may improve with speech therapy over time.",
    "whoUses": "Neurologists, speech-language pathologists, and physiatrists (rehabilitation doctors) use this code when treating stroke patients with speech difficulties. It commonly appears on EOB statements for patients receiving inpatient or outpatient speech therapy following a cerebrovascular event.",
