    "shortDesc": "Dysarthria following unspecified cerebrovascular disease",
    "longDesc": "Dysarthria following unspecified cerebrovascular disease",
    "plainEnglish": "Dysarthria is a speech disorder that makes it difficult to pronounce words clearly or speak smoothly, even though your brain knows what you want to say. This code indicates that your speech difficulty developed after a stroke or other brain blood vessel problem (like bleeding in the brain), though the specific type of cerebrovascular event wasn't documented in detail. You might experience slurred speech, stuttering, or weakness in the muscles you use to speak.",
    "whoUses": "Neurologists, speech-language pathologists, and physiatrists (rehabilitation doctors) commonly use this code when treating stroke recovery and brain injury patients. This code appears on EOB statements for outpatient speech therapy, neurological consultations, and rehabilitation services following cerebrovascular events.",
