    "rawCode": "I69923",
    "shortDesc": "Fluency disorder following unsp cerebrovascular disease",
    "longDesc": "Fluency disorder following unspecified cerebrovascular disease",
    "plainEnglish": "This code describes a speech fluency problem that developed after a stroke or other brain blood vessel injury, when the specific type of cerebrovascular event isn't documented in your medical record. Fluency disorders make it hard to speak smoothly—you might stutter, repeat sounds, or have trouble getting words out—and in this case, the brain damage from the stroke is what's causing the speech difficulty. You may notice you're struggling to speak at a normal pace or rhythm, which is a common recovery challenge after stroke.",
    "whoUses": "Speech-language pathologists, neurologists, and physiatrists (rehabilitation specialists) use this code when treating stroke survivors with speech problems, particularly when the exact type of stroke isn't specified in the chart. It commonly appears on EOB statements for patients receiving speech therapy or stroke rehabilitation services.",
