    "code": "I69.990",
    "rawCode": "I69990",
    "shortDesc": "Apraxia following unspecified cerebrovascular disease",
    "longDesc": "Apraxia following unspecified cerebrovascular disease",
    "plainEnglish": "Apraxia following unspecified cerebrovascular disease means you have lost the ability to perform purposeful, coordinated movements even though your muscles are still working normally. This happened after a stroke or another blood vessel problem in your brain that wasn't specified in detail. You might have trouble performing familiar tasks like getting dressed, eating, or writing, even though you can move your arms and legs and understand what you're trying to do.",
    "whoUses": "Neurologists, physiatrists (rehabilitation medicine doctors), and neuropsychologists use this code when evaluating patients recovering from stroke or other cerebrovascular events. It commonly appears on EOB statements for patients undergoing stroke rehabilitation, occupational therapy, or neuropsychological testing to assess motor planning deficits.",
