    "code": "I69.992",
    "rawCode": "I69992",
    "shortDesc": "Facial weakness following unsp cerebrovascular disease",
    "longDesc": "Facial weakness following unspecified cerebrovascular disease",
    "plainEnglish": "This code describes weakness or drooping of the face that developed after a stroke or other brain blood vessel problem, when the exact type of original brain event isn't specified in the medical record. The weakness typically affects one side of the face and occurs because the stroke or cerebrovascular event damaged the nerves or brain areas that control facial muscles. You might notice difficulty smiling, closing one eye, or puffing out your cheek on the affected side.",
    "whoUses": "Neurologists, stroke specialists, and physical medicine/rehabilitation doctors commonly use this code when treating stroke recovery patients. It frequently appears on EOB statements for patients receiving outpatient therapy, follow-up neurology visits, or rehabilitation services after a cerebrovascular event.",
