    "code": "I70.1",
    "rawCode": "I701",
    "shortDesc": "Atherosclerosis of renal artery",
    "longDesc": "Atherosclerosis of renal artery",
    "plainEnglish": "Atherosclerosis of the renal artery means that fatty plaques have built up inside the blood vessels that carry blood to your kidneys, narrowing the passageways and reducing blood flow to kidney tissue. This buildup happens the same way it does in heart or leg arteries—over time, cholesterol and other substances accumulate on the vessel walls. You may not notice symptoms at first, but reduced kidney blood flow can eventually lead to high blood pressure, kidney damage, or decreased kidney function.",
    "whoUses": "Cardiologists, nephrologists, and vascular surgeons use this code when diagnosing and managing renal artery disease through imaging studies or catheterization. It commonly appears on EOB statements for patients undergoing vascular imaging, angiography, or interventional procedures to treat blocked renal arteries.",
