    "longDesc": "Unspecified atherosclerosis of native arteries of extremities, right leg",
    "plainEnglish": "This code means you have buildup of plaque (fatty deposits) in the arteries of your right leg, but doctors haven't determined the exact severity or specific arteries involved yet. Atherosclerosis happens when cholesterol and other substances accumulate inside artery walls, making them narrower and reducing blood flow to your leg muscles. You might experience leg pain when walking, numbness, coldness in the foot, or slow-healing wounds, depending on how much the blood flow is reduced.",
    "whoUses": "Cardiologists, vascular surgeons, and primary care physicians use this code when evaluating patients with peripheral artery disease (PAD) in the legs. It commonly appears on EOB statements for office visits, ultrasound exams, angiography procedures, or specialist consultations related to leg circulation problems.",
