    "rawCode": "I7025",
    "shortDesc": "Athscl native arteries of extremities w ulceration",
    "longDesc": "Atherosclerosis of native arteries of other extremities with ulceration",
    "plainEnglish": "This diagnosis means you have fatty buildup (plaque) in the arteries that supply blood to your legs, feet, or arms, and this poor blood flow has caused an open sore or ulcer on your skin that won't heal properly. The damaged arteries can't deliver enough oxygen-rich blood to that area, which prevents wounds from healing and can lead to serious complications like infection. Patients typically notice slow-healing sores, pain in the affected limb, or skin that looks pale or discolored.",
    "whoUses": "Vascular surgeons, cardiologists, and interventional radiologists commonly use this code when treating patients with peripheral artery disease (PAD) complicated by non-healing wounds. It frequently appears on patient EOBs when billing for wound care, vascular imaging, or interventional procedures like angioplasty or amputation prevention therapies.",
