    "code": "I70.261",
    "rawCode": "I70261",
    "shortDesc": "Athscl native arteries of extremities w gangrene, right leg",
    "longDesc": "Atherosclerosis of native arteries of extremities with gangrene, right leg",
    "plainEnglish": "This diagnosis means you have severe narrowing of blood vessels in your right leg due to a buildup of plaque (atherosclerosis), which has progressed to the point where tissue in your leg is dying (gangrene). This happens when plaque buildup blocks blood flow so severely that the leg tissues don't get enough oxygen and begin to die, causing discoloration and tissue death. Without treatment, this is a serious condition that may require amputation or other urgent interventions.",
    "whoUses": "Vascular surgeons, cardiologists, and interventional radiologists use this code when treating patients with severe peripheral artery disease affecting the leg. It commonly appears on EOB statements for patients admitted to the hospital for arterial revascularization procedures, amputation, or management of limb-threatening ischemia.",
