    "rawCode": "I70262",
    "shortDesc": "Athscl native arteries of extremities w gangrene, left leg",
    "longDesc": "Atherosclerosis of native arteries of extremities with gangrene, left leg",
    "plainEnglish": "This code describes a serious condition where plaque buildup in the arteries of your left leg has blocked blood flow so severely that part of the tissue is dying (gangrene). Gangrene happens when cells don't get enough oxygen-rich blood and begin to die, which typically causes discoloration, pain, and tissue deterioration in the affected leg. This is a medical emergency that usually requires immediate treatment, which may include surgery to remove the dead tissue or even amputation to prevent the infection from spreading.",
    "whoUses": "Vascular surgeons, interventional cardiologists, and general surgeons primarily use this code when treating patients with severe peripheral artery disease and tissue death. This code commonly appears on patient EOBs for hospital inpatient procedures (such as arterial bypass, endarterectomy, or amputation) and is associated with significant healthcare costs and prolonged recovery.",
