    "longDesc": "Other atherosclerosis of native arteries of extremities, right leg",
    "plainEnglish": "This diagnosis means you have buildup of plaque (a fatty substance) in the blood vessels of your right leg that supply blood to your muscles and tissues. This narrowing of the arteries reduces blood flow, which can cause pain or cramping in your leg when you walk or exercise, numbness, or in severe cases, tissue damage. The buildup develops gradually over time and is related to high cholesterol, high blood pressure, smoking, and other risk factors.",
    "whoUses": "Cardiologists, vascular surgeons, interventional radiologists, and primary care physicians commonly use this code when diagnosing and treating peripheral arterial disease. You will likely see this code on your EOB if you've had imaging studies (ultrasound, angiography) or procedures to evaluate leg blood flow, or if you're being treated for leg pain or circulation problems.",
