    "longDesc": "Other atherosclerosis of native arteries of extremities, bilateral legs",
    "plainEnglish": "This diagnosis means you have buildup of plaque (a sticky combination of fat, cholesterol, and other substances) in the arteries of both of your legs that supply blood to your lower extremities. This narrowing of the arteries restricts blood flow to your legs and feet, which can cause pain during walking, numbness, coldness, or even tissue damage if left untreated. The condition develops over time and is related to factors like age, smoking, high cholesterol, high blood pressure, and diabetes.",
    "whoUses": "Cardiologists, vascular surgeons, interventional radiologists, and primary care physicians commonly use this code when patients present with peripheral artery disease affecting both legs. It frequently appears on EOB statements when patients undergo vascular imaging, arterial interventions, or are managed medically for chronic arterial insufficiency of the lower extremities.",
