    "longDesc": "Other atherosclerosis of native arteries of extremities, unspecified extremity",
    "plainEnglish": "This code describes buildup of plaque (a fatty, waxy substance) in the blood vessels of your arms or legs, but the specific location isn't documented in your medical record. This condition, called atherosclerosis, narrows your arteries and can reduce blood flow to your limbs, potentially causing pain, weakness, or poor wound healing. You might notice symptoms like leg or arm pain when walking or exercising, or you might have no symptoms at all if the blockage is mild.",
    "whoUses": "Cardiologists, vascular surgeons, primary care physicians, and interventional radiologists use this code when diagnosing peripheral artery disease during physical exams, imaging studies, or catheterization procedures. It commonly appears on EOB statements for patients undergoing vascular testing, angiography, or treatment for reduced circulation in their extremities.",
