    "rawCode": "I7090",
    "shortDesc": "Unspecified atherosclerosis",
    "longDesc": "Unspecified atherosclerosis",
    "plainEnglish": "Atherosclerosis is a condition where fatty deposits (plaque) build up inside your arteries, narrowing the blood vessels and reducing blood flow to your heart, brain, legs, and other organs. This code is used when a doctor has diagnosed you with atherosclerosis but hasn't specified which blood vessels are affected or how severe it is. Over time, atherosclerosis can lead to serious complications like heart attacks or strokes if the narrowed arteries become completely blocked.",
    "whoUses": "Cardiologists, internists, and vascular surgeons commonly use this code when documenting atherosclerosis during initial diagnosis or when the specific location isn't yet determined. It frequently appears on EOB statements for patients undergoing cardiac workups, imaging studies, or consultations for cardiovascular risk factors.",
