    "shortDesc": "Generalized atherosclerosis",
    "longDesc": "Generalized atherosclerosis",
    "plainEnglish": "Generalized atherosclerosis means plaque buildup has occurred in multiple blood vessels throughout your body, not just in one location. This happens when cholesterol, fat, and other substances accumulate inside artery walls over time, narrowing the vessels and restricting blood flow to your organs and tissues. You may not have symptoms initially, but this condition increases your risk for heart attacks, strokes, and circulation problems in your legs.",
    "whoUses": "Cardiologists, vascular surgeons, primary care physicians, and internists commonly use this code when documenting widespread artery disease affecting multiple organ systems. It frequently appears on EOB statements for patients with multiple cardiovascular risk factors or who are undergoing vascular imaging studies, angiography, or preventive cardiology evaluations.",
