    "shortDesc": "Dissection of abdominal aorta",
    "longDesc": "Dissection of abdominal aorta",
    "plainEnglish": "A dissection of the abdominal aorta occurs when the inner lining of the major blood vessel that carries blood from your heart to your abdomen tears, allowing blood to seep between the layers of the artery wall. This creates a false channel within the vessel that can reduce blood flow to vital organs like your kidneys, intestines, and legs, and poses a serious risk of rupture. Symptoms may include sudden severe abdominal or back pain, chest pain, or signs of reduced blood flow to organs (such as leg pain or numbness).",
    "whoUses": "Vascular surgeons, cardiothoracic surgeons, interventional radiologists, and emergency medicine physicians diagnose and treat aortic dissection. This is a life-threatening condition that typically appears in acute hospital or emergency settings rather than on routine EOB statements, though it may appear on claims following emergency imaging (CT angiography) or surgical intervention.",
