    "plainEnglish": "An abdominal aortic aneurysm (AAA) is a weakened area in the wall of your aorta—the large artery that carries blood from your heart down through your abdomen. Over time, this weakened section bulges outward like a balloon, and if it continues to enlarge, it could potentially rupture and cause life-threatening bleeding. This code indicates you have been diagnosed with an AAA that hasn't ruptured yet, though the exact size or specific location within your abdomen hasn't been documented in detail.",
    "whoUses": "Vascular surgeons, interventional radiologists, and cardiologists commonly use this code when managing patients with known AAA, typically discovered during ultrasound or CT imaging. It frequently appears on EOB statements for patients undergoing surveillance imaging, consultations, or treatment planning for AAA, and helps justify ongoing monitoring or preventive intervention.",
    "billable": true,
    "isNew": false,
    "isRevised": false,
