    "rawCode": "I722",
    "shortDesc": "Aneurysm of renal artery",
    "longDesc": "Aneurysm of renal artery",
    "plainEnglish": "A renal artery aneurysm is a bulging or weakening in the wall of the blood vessel that carries blood to your kidney, which can cause it to balloon outward. Most people with this condition have no symptoms and discover it by chance during imaging tests for other reasons, though in rare cases it can rupture and cause serious internal bleeding. The weakening can be caused by high blood pressure, fibromuscular dysplasia (an inherited connective tissue condition), or atherosclerosis (hardening of the arteries).",
    "whoUses": "Vascular surgeons, interventional radiologists, and nephrologists (kidney specialists) typically diagnose and manage renal artery aneurysms using imaging and minimally invasive procedures. This code appears on EOBs when a patient undergoes imaging studies (CT, MRI, or ultrasound), angiography, or surgical/interventional treatment for a detected aneurysm.",
