    "shortDesc": "Aneurysm of iliac artery",
    "longDesc": "Aneurysm of iliac artery",
    "plainEnglish": "An aneurysm of the iliac artery is a bulging or weakening in the wall of one of the large blood vessels in your lower abdomen and pelvis that carries blood to your legs. This bulging can happen due to high blood pressure, atherosclerosis (hardening of the arteries), connective tissue disorders, or sometimes injury, and it may not cause any symptoms at first. However, if the aneurysm ruptures or becomes very large, it can cause severe pain, internal bleeding, or life-threatening complications that require emergency surgery.",
    "whoUses": "Vascular surgeons, interventional radiologists, and general surgeons commonly diagnose and treat iliac artery aneurysms, often using imaging studies like ultrasound, CT scans, or angiography. This code appears on patient EOBs when diagnostic imaging, monitoring, or surgical repair of the aneurysm is performed, and may be accompanied by codes for procedures like endovascular stent placement or open surgical repair.",
