    "shortDesc": "Raynaud's syndrome without gangrene",
    "longDesc": "Raynaud's syndrome without gangrene",
    "plainEnglish": "Raynaud's syndrome is a condition where small blood vessels in your fingers and toes overreact to cold exposure or stress, causing them to narrow and temporarily cut off blood flow to those areas. This results in your fingers or toes turning white, then blue, and finally red as the blood flow returns, often accompanied by numbness, tingling, or pain. The \"without gangrene\" part means the tissue isn't dying or permanently damaged, which is the less severe form of this condition.",
    "whoUses": "Rheumatologists, primary care physicians, and vascular specialists most commonly diagnose and manage Raynaud's syndrome. This code appears on patient EOB statements when patients present with symptoms of episodic finger/toe discoloration triggered by cold or emotional stress, and it's relatively common in patients with connective tissue disorders or as a primary condition.",
