    "plainEnglish": "Raynaud's syndrome with gangrene is a serious condition where blood vessels in your fingers or toes overreact to cold or stress by narrowing severely, cutting off blood flow to the tissue. When this happens repeatedly over time without adequate blood supply, the affected tissue dies (a process called gangrene), which can result in tissue damage or loss that may require treatment or even amputation. This is an advanced stage of Raynaud's syndrome and represents a medical emergency requiring immediate attention.",
    "whoUses": "Rheumatologists, vascular surgeons, and dermatologists primarily use this code when patients with Raynaud's syndrome develop the serious complication of tissue death. This code is less common on patient EOBs than the uncomplicated Raynaud's codes but appears when hospital admissions or specialist consultations occur for severe, complications cases requiring urgent intervention.",
