    "shortDesc": "Saddle embolus of abdominal aorta",
    "longDesc": "Saddle embolus of abdominal aorta",
    "plainEnglish": "A saddle embolus of the abdominal aorta is a blood clot that has lodged at the point where the main artery in your belly (abdominal aorta) splits into two branches, blocking blood flow to your lower body and legs. This is a medical emergency because it cuts off blood supply to your abdomen and legs, which can cause severe pain, numbness, weakness, and tissue damage if not treated immediately. You would need emergency surgery or intervention to remove the clot and restore blood flow.",
