    "code": "I75.011",
    "rawCode": "I75011",
    "shortDesc": "Atheroembolism of right upper extremity",
    "longDesc": "Atheroembolism of right upper extremity",
    "plainEnglish": "Atheroembolism of the right upper extremity means that a blood clot or fatty plaque particle has broken loose from a larger plaque deposit in an artery and traveled to block a blood vessel in your right arm or hand. This sudden blockage can restrict blood flow, potentially causing pain, numbness, coldness, or skin discoloration in that arm. The condition typically occurs when existing atherosclerotic plaques (hardened cholesterol buildup) in larger arteries become unstable and pieces break off.",
    "whoUses": "Cardiologists, vascular surgeons, and interventional radiologists commonly diagnose and treat atheroembolism using imaging and catheter-based procedures. This code appears on EOB statements when patients undergo vascular imaging (ultrasound, CT angiography) or interventional treatment, though it is less common on routine patient EOBs and more frequently used in hospital billing and specialist documentation.",
