    "code": "I77.4",
    "rawCode": "I774",
    "shortDesc": "Celiac artery compression syndrome",
    "longDesc": "Celiac artery compression syndrome",
    "plainEnglish": "Celiac artery compression syndrome occurs when tissue or structures in your abdomen compress (squeeze) the celiac artery, a major blood vessel that supplies blood to your stomach, liver, and other organs. This compression can restrict blood flow to these organs, causing you to experience abdominal pain (especially after eating), weight loss, or digestive problems. The condition is sometimes called median arcuate ligament syndrome when a fibrous band near your diaphragm is the cause of the compression.",
    "whoUses": "Vascular surgeons, general surgeons, and gastroenterologists use this code when diagnosing and treating patients with symptomatic celiac artery compression. While it is a legitimate diagnosis, it is relatively uncommon and may not frequently appear on routine patient EOB statements unless the patient undergoes vascular imaging or surgical intervention for this specific condition.",
