    "code": "I77.6",
    "rawCode": "I776",
    "shortDesc": "Arteritis, unspecified",
    "longDesc": "Arteritis, unspecified",
    "plainEnglish": "Arteritis means inflammation of your arteries (the blood vessels that carry blood away from your heart). When doctors use the term \"unspecified,\" it means they've diagnosed you with arterial inflammation but haven't yet determined the specific cause—it could be related to an infection, autoimmune condition, or other underlying issue. You might experience symptoms like pain, weakness, or numbness in the affected area, depending on which arteries are involved.",
    "whoUses": "Vascular surgeons, cardiologists, internists, and rheumatologists commonly use this code when evaluating patients with inflamed arteries but before a definitive diagnosis is made. This code frequently appears on patient EOB statements during the diagnostic phase, often followed by a more specific diagnosis code once testing identifies the underlying cause.",
