    "shortDesc": "Dissection of renal artery",
    "longDesc": "Dissection of renal artery",
    "plainEnglish": "A dissection of your renal artery means that the inner lining of the artery that carries blood to your kidney has torn, creating a flap that can slow down or block blood flow to that kidney. This is a serious condition that can happen suddenly from trauma, high blood pressure, or sometimes without a clear cause, and you might experience sudden flank or back pain, high blood pressure, or reduced kidney function. Treatment depends on how severe the dissection is and may range from careful monitoring with imaging studies to surgery or other interventional procedures to restore blood flow.",
    "whoUses": "Vascular surgeons, interventional radiologists, nephrologists, and cardiologists typically diagnose and treat renal artery dissection. This code commonly appears on hospital claims and specialist referral records when a patient is hospitalized or undergoes imaging/intervention, though it may also appear on EOBs for follow-up imaging or specialist consultations.",
