    "shortDesc": "Phlebitis and thombophlb of superfic vessels of r low extrem",
    "longDesc": "Phlebitis and thrombophlebitis of superficial vessels of right lower extremity",
    "plainEnglish": "This code describes inflammation of a vein (phlebitis) combined with a blood clot (thrombophlebitis) in the veins just beneath the skin on your right leg. You may notice redness, warmth, swelling, or tenderness along the affected vein, usually appearing as a cord-like area. This condition often develops after injury, prolonged immobility, surgery, or in people with certain blood clotting disorders, and while uncomfortable, superficial clots are generally less serious than deep vein clots.",
    "whoUses": "Vascular surgeons, emergency medicine physicians, general practitioners, and internists use this code when diagnosing and treating leg vein inflammation. It commonly appears on patient EOBs when someone seeks care for leg pain, swelling, or visible vein inflammation, and is frequently documented during emergency department visits or urgent care evaluations.",
