    "plainEnglish": "You have inflammation of a vein in your left leg, near the surface of the skin, with a blood clot forming inside it. This condition causes pain, swelling, redness, and warmth along the affected vein, typically in the lower leg or thigh. While superficial blood clots are usually less dangerous than deep vein clots, they still require medical attention to prevent complications and manage your symptoms.",
    "whoUses": "Vascular surgeons, general practitioners, emergency medicine doctors, and cardiologists commonly diagnose and treat this condition in hospital, urgent care, and outpatient settings. This code frequently appears on patient EOB statements because superficial thrombophlebitis requires imaging (ultrasound), clinical visits, and sometimes anticoagulation therapy or other interventions.",
