    "code": "I82.0",
    "rawCode": "I820",
    "shortDesc": "Budd-Chiari syndrome",
    "longDesc": "Budd-Chiari syndrome",
    "plainEnglish": "Budd-Chiari syndrome is a rare blood clot that forms in the veins that drain blood from your liver, blocking normal blood flow out of the organ. This blockage causes blood to back up in the liver, leading to swelling of the abdomen, an enlarged liver, and potentially serious liver damage if not treated. You might experience sudden severe abdominal pain, swelling in your legs, or signs of liver failure depending on how quickly the clot formed.",
    "whoUses": "Hepatologists, gastroenterologists, and vascular surgeons diagnose and manage Budd-Chiari syndrome, often using imaging studies and blood work to confirm the diagnosis. This code appears on patient EOBs when someone receives treatment for this condition, though it is relatively uncommon and may trigger coverage questions due to its rarity.",
