    "rawCode": "I821",
    "shortDesc": "Thrombophlebitis migrans",
    "longDesc": "Thrombophlebitis migrans",
    "plainEnglish": "Thrombophlebitis migrans is a condition where blood clots form in surface veins and the inflammation moves or spreads from one vein to another over time. This means you develop painful, red, and swollen areas along veins that seem to appear in different locations on your body rather than staying in one spot. While it can occur on its own, it's sometimes a sign of an underlying serious condition like cancer or an autoimmune disorder, so doctors usually investigate the cause when this diagnosis appears.",
    "whoUses": "Vascular surgeons, cardiologists, hematologists, and internists use this code when patients present with migratory thrombophlebitis, typically in hospital or urgent care settings. It appears on EOB statements when patients have had imaging studies, anticoagulation therapy, or specialist consultations related to this condition.",
