    "rawCode": "I82211",
    "shortDesc": "Chronic embolism and thrombosis of superior vena cava",
    "longDesc": "Chronic embolism and thrombosis of superior vena cava",
    "plainEnglish": "This diagnosis means you have a blood clot (thrombosis) or blockage in the superior vena cava, which is the large vein that carries blood from your upper body and head back to your heart, and this clot has been present for a long time rather than occurring suddenly. Chronic blood clots in this vein can develop gradually due to conditions like cancer, infection, or previous injuries, and may cause symptoms such as swelling in the arms, neck, and face, or reduced blood flow to the upper body.",
    "whoUses": "Cardiologists, vascular surgeons, interventional radiologists, and oncologists commonly diagnose and treat this condition, particularly in patients with malignancies or central venous catheters. This code frequently appears on EOB statements for patients undergoing imaging studies (ultrasound, CT, or venography), anticoagulation therapy management, or interventional procedures to restore blood flow.",
