    "longDesc": "Acute embolism and thrombosis of inferior vena cava",
    "plainEnglish": "This diagnosis means a blood clot has suddenly formed in the inferior vena cava, the large vein that carries blood from your lower body back to your heart. This is a serious condition because the clot can block blood flow and potentially break loose and travel to your lungs, causing a life-threatening complication. You may experience swelling in your legs, pain, or shortness of breath, depending on how much the clot is blocking blood flow.",
    "whoUses": "Vascular surgeons, interventional radiologists, emergency medicine physicians, and cardiologists manage this condition, which is typically diagnosed in acute care settings like emergency departments or intensive care units. This code commonly appears on EOB statements for patients requiring emergency care, imaging studies (such as CT or ultrasound), and possible catheter-based clot removal procedures.",
