    "shortDesc": "Chronic embolism and thrombosis of inferior vena cava",
    "longDesc": "Chronic embolism and thrombosis of inferior vena cava",
    "plainEnglish": "This means you have a long-term blood clot in the inferior vena cava, the large vein that carries blood from your lower body back to your heart. The clot has been present for weeks or months (chronic), and it may partially or completely block blood flow in that vein. You might experience swelling in your legs, abdomen, or lower back, along with pain, skin discoloration, or varicose veins as your body tries to route blood around the blockage.",
    "whoUses": "Vascular surgeons, interventional radiologists, cardiologists, and pulmonologists use this code when managing patients with blood clots in the inferior vena cava. It commonly appears on EOB statements for patients undergoing imaging studies, anticoagulation therapy, or procedures to remove or treat the clot.",
