    "shortDesc": "Embolism and thrombosis of renal vein",
    "longDesc": "Embolism and thrombosis of renal vein",
    "plainEnglish": "This code describes a blood clot (thrombosis) or blockage (embolism) in the renal vein, which is the large blood vessel that carries blood away from the kidney back to the heart. When this vein becomes blocked, it can reduce blood flow from the kidney, potentially causing back pain, blood in the urine, or even kidney damage if not treated. This condition can develop due to trauma, cancer, kidney disease, or blood clotting disorders, and requires medical evaluation to determine the cause and prevent complications.",
    "whoUses": "Nephrologists (kidney specialists), vascular surgeons, and interventional radiologists commonly diagnose and treat this condition using imaging studies and anticoagulation therapy. This code appears on patient EOBs when renal vein thrombosis is diagnosed, typically following ultrasound, CT scan, or MRI confirmation, and is used to justify imaging, monitoring, or treatment-related claims.",
