    "plainEnglish": "This diagnosis means a blood clot has suddenly formed in the tibial vein (a major vein in your lower leg on the right side) that is blocking blood flow. This can happen after surgery, prolonged immobility, or certain medical conditions, and you may notice swelling, pain, redness, or warmth in your calf or leg. If not treated, this clot could potentially break loose and travel to your lungs, which is why it requires prompt medical attention.",
    "whoUses": "Vascular surgeons, interventional radiologists, cardiologists, and emergency medicine physicians use this code when diagnosing and treating deep vein thrombosis (DVT). It commonly appears on EOB statements for patients hospitalized or evaluated in emergency departments for leg swelling or who undergo ultrasound imaging or CT scans to confirm the clot.",
