    "plainEnglish": "A blood clot has suddenly formed in the peroneal vein, which is a deep vein in your right leg that runs along the smaller bone (fibula). This happens when blood flow slows or stops in this vessel, allowing platelets and fibrin to stick together and block the vein. You may experience swelling, pain, warmth, or redness in your right calf or leg, and there's a risk the clot could break loose and travel to your lungs (a serious emergency).",
    "whoUses": "Vascular surgeons, interventional radiologists, emergency medicine physicians, and hospitalists use this code when diagnosing deep vein thrombosis (DVT) of the peroneal vein. It appears on patient EOBs when imaging (ultrasound or CT) confirms acute clot formation and typically triggers urgent anticoagulation therapy or possible intervention.",
