    "rawCode": "I82511",
    "shortDesc": "Chronic embolism and thrombosis of right femoral vein",
    "longDesc": "Chronic embolism and thrombosis of right femoral vein",
    "plainEnglish": "You have a blood clot in your right femoral vein (the large vein in your thigh) that has been present for a long time or keeps coming back. This chronic clot restricts blood flow in your leg, which can cause swelling, pain, discoloration, or heaviness in your right thigh and calf. The condition develops over time rather than suddenly, and your body may form new clots or the original clot may not fully dissolve despite treatment.",
    "whoUses": "Vascular surgeons, interventional radiologists, and general practitioners use this code when managing patients with long-standing leg vein clots that require ongoing monitoring or treatment. It commonly appears on EOB statements for patients undergoing imaging, anticoagulation therapy, or vascular procedures related to chronic deep vein thrombosis.",
