    "code": "I82.549",
    "rawCode": "I82549",
    "shortDesc": "Chronic embolism and thrombosis of unspecified tibial vein",
    "longDesc": "Chronic embolism and thrombosis of unspecified tibial vein",
    "plainEnglish": "You have a blood clot that has formed in one of the tibial veins (the veins in your lower leg below the knee) that has persisted over time or keeps recurring. This chronic clot restricts blood flow in your leg and can cause swelling, pain, heaviness, or skin discoloration in the affected leg. The clot is \"unspecified\" because your doctor hasn't documented which of the two tibial veins (anterior or posterior) is affected, or the information wasn't clearly identified in your medical records.",
    "whoUses": "Vascular surgeons, interventional radiologists, and phlebologists use this code when managing long-standing leg vein clots, typically discovered during ultrasound evaluation or when patients present with chronic leg swelling. This code appears on EOB statements when patients have had imaging studies, office visits, or procedures related to evaluation and treatment of deep vein thrombosis (DVT).",
