    "longDesc": "Chronic embolism and thrombosis of peroneal vein, bilateral",
    "plainEnglish": "You have blood clots in both of your peroneal veins (deep veins in your calves), and this condition is chronic, meaning it has been ongoing for a while. The peroneal veins are responsible for draining blood from your lower legs back to your heart, so a blockage can cause swelling, pain, or discoloration in your calves and feet. This long-standing clotting requires ongoing monitoring and treatment to prevent the clot from breaking loose and traveling to your lungs.",
    "whoUses": "Vascular surgeons, cardiologists, and interventional radiologists most commonly use this code when managing patients with deep vein thrombosis (DVT). It appears on EOBs when patients undergo imaging studies, clinic visits, or procedures related to chronic venous thromboembolism management.",
