    "rawCode": "I82601",
    "shortDesc": "Acute embolism and thombos unsp veins of r up extrem",
    "longDesc": "Acute embolism and thrombosis of unspecified veins of right upper extremity",
    "plainEnglish": "This code describes a blood clot that has suddenly formed in one of the veins in your right arm or shoulder. The clot either traveled from somewhere else in your body (embolism) or formed directly in that vein (thrombosis), blocking blood flow. You might experience sudden swelling, pain, warmth, or redness in your right arm, and the condition requires prompt medical attention to prevent the clot from traveling to your lungs or causing permanent damage.",
    "whoUses": "Vascular surgeons, interventional radiologists, emergency medicine physicians, and hospitalists use this code when diagnosing and treating acute upper extremity clots, often confirmed with ultrasound or CT imaging. It commonly appears on EOB statements for patients admitted to the hospital or visiting the emergency department with acute arm swelling and clotting symptoms.",
