    "longDesc": "Acute embolism and thrombosis of unspecified veins of left upper extremity",
    "plainEnglish": "This diagnosis means you have a blood clot that has formed and is traveling through the veins in your left arm. The clot developed suddenly and is blocking blood flow in one or more veins, which can cause swelling, pain, warmth, and redness in your arm. This is a serious condition that needs prompt treatment to prevent the clot from traveling to your lungs or causing permanent damage to the arm.",
    "whoUses": "Vascular surgeons, cardiologists, emergency medicine physicians, and hospitalists commonly diagnose and treat this condition in acute care settings such as emergency departments or hospital wards. This code frequently appears on patient EOB statements because the condition typically requires hospital admission, imaging studies (ultrasound or CT), and anticoagulation therapy.",
