    "shortDesc": "Sublingual varices",
    "longDesc": "Sublingual varices",
    "plainEnglish": "Sublingual varices are abnormally enlarged and twisted veins located under your tongue. This condition develops when blood pools in these small veins, causing them to become swollen and prominent, which you might notice as bluish or purplish bumps or cord-like structures beneath your tongue. While sublingual varices are usually harmless and don't cause symptoms, they can occasionally bleed or become uncomfortable, especially if accidentally bitten or irritated.",
    "whoUses": "Dentists, general practitioners, and otolaryngologists (ENT specialists) most commonly identify and monitor sublingual varices during routine oral exams or when patients report changes in the appearance under their tongue. This code rarely appears on patient EOB statements unless the varices are specifically treated or require specialist evaluation, as they typically don't require active medical intervention.",
