    "longDesc": "Postthrombotic syndrome without complications of left lower extremity",
    "plainEnglish": "Postthrombotic syndrome is a long-term condition that develops after you've had a blood clot (deep vein thrombosis) in your leg, usually in the deep veins below the knee. Even after the clot dissolves or is treated, the damage to the vein valves can cause persistent problems like swelling, pain, heaviness, or skin changes in your leg. This code specifically indicates you have this condition in your left leg without any serious complications.",
    "whoUses": "Vascular surgeons, cardiologists, interventional radiologists, and primary care physicians use this code when managing patients with a history of deep vein thrombosis who develop chronic venous insufficiency symptoms. It commonly appears on EOB statements for patients seeking follow-up care, compression therapy, or evaluation for ongoing leg symptoms months or years after a blood clot.",
