    "rawCode": "I87003",
    "shortDesc": "Postthrom syndrome w/o complications of bilateral low extrm",
    "longDesc": "Postthrombotic syndrome without complications of bilateral lower extremity",
    "plainEnglish": "Postthrombotic syndrome is a long-term condition that develops after you've had a blood clot (thrombosis) in the veins of your legs. When a clot forms and then dissolves or is treated, it can damage the valves inside your veins, making it harder for blood to flow back up toward your heart. This code specifically means you have this condition affecting both legs without any current serious complications like open sores or severe swelling. You might experience symptoms like aching, heaviness, swelling, or skin discoloration in your legs that worsens throughout the day.",
    "whoUses": "Vascular surgeons, interventional radiologists, and primary care physicians use this code when managing patients with a history of deep vein thrombosis. It commonly appears on EOB statements for patients receiving ongoing care, compression therapy, or follow-up appointments related to previous blood clots in the legs.",
