    "code": "I87.012",
    "rawCode": "I87012",
    "shortDesc": "Postthrombotic syndrome with ulcer of left lower extremity",
    "longDesc": "Postthrombotic syndrome with ulcer of left lower extremity",
    "plainEnglish": "Postthrombotic syndrome is a long-term condition that develops after you've had a blood clot (usually in your leg), where the clot damages the valves in your veins and causes poor blood circulation. When this condition leads to an open sore or ulcer on your left lower leg or foot that won't heal properly, it's coded as this diagnosis. This happens because the damaged veins can't pump blood back up from your leg efficiently, causing fluid buildup, skin breakdown, and slow-healing wounds.",
    "whoUses": "Vascular surgeons, interventional radiologists, wound care specialists, and general surgeons commonly use this code when treating patients with chronic leg ulcers related to previous blood clots. It frequently appears on patient EOB statements for people with documented histories of deep vein thrombosis (DVT) who develop complicated skin ulcers requiring ongoing treatment.",
