    "code": "I87.311",
    "rawCode": "I87311",
    "shortDesc": "Chronic venous hypertension w ulcer of r low extrem",
    "longDesc": "Chronic venous hypertension (idiopathic) with ulcer of right lower extremity",
    "plainEnglish": "This code describes a condition where blood pressure in the veins of your right leg is chronically elevated for reasons that aren't clearly understood, and this has caused an open sore or ulcer to develop on that leg. Venous hypertension happens when veins have trouble pumping blood back up to your heart, causing pressure to build up in the leg; over time, this weakens the skin and underlying tissues, leading to painful wounds that are slow to heal.",
    "whoUses": "Vascular surgeons, dermatologists, and wound care specialists commonly use this code when treating patients with chronic leg ulcers related to venous insufficiency. It frequently appears on EOB statements for patients receiving ongoing wound care, compression therapy, or vein procedures.",
