    "code": "I87.9",
    "rawCode": "I879",
    "shortDesc": "Disorder of vein, unspecified",
    "longDesc": "Disorder of vein, unspecified",
    "plainEnglish": "This code is used when a patient has a problem with their veins, but the specific type of vein disorder hasn't been clearly identified or documented. Veins are blood vessels that carry blood back to the heart, and they can develop various issues like blood clots, weakness, swelling, or valve problems. Your doctor used this general code likely because further testing or clarification is needed to pinpoint exactly what's wrong with your veins.",
    "whoUses": "Vascular surgeons, cardiologists, internists, and emergency medicine physicians use this code when a patient presents with vein-related symptoms but the underlying condition isn't yet specified. It commonly appears on EOB statements as a temporary or preliminary diagnosis code while the patient is being evaluated or before a more specific vein disorder diagnosis is confirmed.",
