    "rawCode": "I880",
    "shortDesc": "Nonspecific mesenteric lymphadenitis",
    "longDesc": "Nonspecific mesenteric lymphadenitis",
    "plainEnglish": "Nonspecific mesenteric lymphadenitis means the lymph nodes in the membrane that holds your intestines (the mesentery) have become swollen and inflamed, but doctors haven't identified a specific cause like a bacteria or virus. You might experience abdominal pain, tenderness around your belly, and possibly fever or nausea. This condition is usually temporary and often resolves on its own, though it can sometimes mimic appendicitis or other serious abdominal problems.",
    "whoUses": "Gastroenterologists, emergency medicine physicians, and general surgeons use this code when evaluating patients with abdominal pain—it commonly appears on imaging reports (CT scans) and in ER settings. While it may appear on EOBs for imaging or ER visits, it's not typically a primary billing diagnosis since it's often a finding rather than the main reason for treatment.",
