    "plainEnglish": "Idiopathic hypotension means your blood pressure is persistently lower than normal, but doctors cannot identify a specific cause for it. This occurs when your body's blood pressure regulation system doesn't maintain adequate pressure on its own, which may cause symptoms like dizziness, fatigue, or fainting when you stand up or exert yourself. Unlike secondary hypotension (which results from another condition), this type happens without an underlying disease or medication being responsible.",
    "whoUses": "Primary care physicians, cardiologists, and internists use this code when diagnosing patients with chronic low blood pressure of unknown origin. It appears fairly commonly on EOB statements for patients experiencing unexplained hypotension who require ongoing monitoring and management.",
