    "longDesc": "Postprocedural hypotension",
    "plainEnglish": "Postprocedural hypotension is a drop in blood pressure that occurs as a direct result of a medical procedure or surgery. This can happen during or shortly after the procedure as your body reacts to anesthesia, blood loss, medications, or the stress of the procedure itself. You might experience dizziness, lightheadedness, weakness, or blurred vision, and your medical team will monitor and treat this by adjusting fluids, medications, or positioning to bring your blood pressure back to normal.",
    "whoUses": "Anesthesiologists, surgeons, and operating room staff commonly document this code during or immediately after surgical procedures. It also appears in post-acute care settings like hospitals and recovery centers. This code frequently shows up on patient EOB statements when a complication occurs during a hospital stay or surgical procedure.",
