    "longDesc": "Postmastectomy lymphedema syndrome",
    "plainEnglish": "Postmastectomy lymphedema syndrome is swelling that develops in the arm, hand, or chest wall after breast cancer surgery (mastectomy) or lymph node removal. This happens because the surgery disrupts the normal drainage of lymphatic fluid, causing it to accumulate in the tissues rather than flowing properly through the body. Patients typically notice progressive swelling, heaviness, tightness, or reduced mobility in the affected area, and the condition can develop weeks, months, or even years after surgery.",
    "whoUses": "This code is used by surgical oncologists, breast surgeons, and physical/occupational therapists who manage post-surgical complications in breast cancer patients. It commonly appears on EOB statements for patients receiving lymphedema treatment, compression therapy, or rehabilitation services following mastectomy or axillary lymph node dissection.",
