    "shortDesc": "Postprocedural hypertension",
    "longDesc": "Postprocedural hypertension",
    "plainEnglish": "Postprocedural hypertension is high blood pressure that develops as a direct result of a medical procedure or surgery you've had. This can happen immediately after the procedure or within a short time afterward, and it occurs because the procedure itself triggered a temporary spike in blood pressure—perhaps due to pain, stress, anesthesia, or inflammation from the intervention. Usually this elevated blood pressure resolves on its own once your body recovers from the procedure, though your doctor may monitor it closely to make sure it returns to normal levels.",
    "whoUses": "Cardiologists, anesthesiologists, surgeons, and hospitalists commonly use this code to document blood pressure complications in the immediate postoperative period across all surgical specialties. It typically appears on hospital bills and EOB statements when high blood pressure was noted and documented as a complication during or shortly after a procedure.",
