    "code": "I97.810",
    "rawCode": "I97810",
    "shortDesc": "Intraoperative cerebvasc infarction during cardiac surgery",
    "longDesc": "Intraoperative cerebrovascular infarction during cardiac surgery",
    "plainEnglish": "This code describes a stroke that happens during heart surgery—specifically, a blood clot or blocked blood vessel in the brain that occurs while the surgeon is operating on the heart. During cardiac procedures, especially those involving bypass machines or manipulation of major blood vessels, there is a small risk that a clot can form and travel to the brain or that blood flow to the brain can be interrupted, causing brain tissue to die from lack of oxygen. Patients may experience weakness, numbness, speech problems, or other stroke symptoms either immediately after surgery or discovered during recovery.",
    "whoUses": "Cardiac surgeons and cardiothoracic surgical teams use this code to document post-operative stroke complications, typically in hospital settings after procedures like bypass grafting, valve repair, or transplantation. This code occasionally appears on patient EOB statements as a post-operative complication, usually accompanied by significant hospital charges since it requires intensive care and additional stroke treatment.",
