    "rawCode": "I97820",
    "shortDesc": "Postproc cerebvasc infarction following cardiac surgery",
    "longDesc": "Postprocedural cerebrovascular infarction following cardiac surgery",
    "plainEnglish": "This diagnosis means you had a stroke (a blood clot blocking blood flow to part of your brain) that occurred as a complication after you had heart surgery. During or shortly after your cardiac procedure, something disrupted normal blood flow to your brain, causing brain tissue to die from lack of oxygen. This is a serious but recognized risk that can happen even when surgery goes well, and you may experience sudden weakness, numbness, speech difficulties, or vision problems depending on which part of your brain was affected.",
    "whoUses": "Cardiologists, cardiac surgeons, neurologists, and interventional radiologists use this code when documenting stroke complications following heart procedures like bypass surgery, valve replacement, or coronary interventions. This code typically appears on hospital bills and EOB statements as a complication charge, often triggering additional medical review and potentially affecting insurance coverage or quality metrics for the surgical facility.",
